:"1562","about 1521":"circa 1521","1549":"1549","1604":"1604","1559":"1559","1603":"1603","England":"England","Sudbury, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sudbury, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sudbury, Suffolk, England":"Sudbury, Suffolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1522–1591":"1522–1591","1530–1591":"1530–1591","1562–1603":"1562–1603","1560–1604":"1560–1604","1497–Male":"1497–Deceased","1501–Female":"1501–Deceased","from 1560 to 1575":"from 1560 to 1575","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","1591":"1591","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1522":"1522","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1497":"1497","1530":"1530","1562":"1562","about 1521":"about 1521","1549":"1549","1604":"1604","1559":"1559","1603":"1603","England":"England","Sudbury, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sudbury, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Sudbury, Suffolk, England":"Sudbury, Suffolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dandridge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Dundridge in Bishop's Waltham, Hampshire."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":27,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":36,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":47,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":49,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":63,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":65,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Dandridge was born in 1522, in Sudbury, Suffolk, England, his father, Thomas Dandridge, was 25 and his mother, Mrs Thomas Danridge, was 21. He married Margaret Joan Bert in 1559, in Sudbury, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1591, in England, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1522–1591":"1522–1591","1530–1591":"1530–1591","1562–1603":"1562–1603","1560–1604":"1560–1604","1497–Male":"1497–Surnud","1501–Female":"1501–Surnud","from 1560 to 1575":"1560 kuni 1575","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","1591":"1591","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1522":"1522","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1497":"1497","1530":"1530","1562":"1562","about 1521":"umbes 1521","1549":"1549","1604":"1604","1559":"1559","1603":"1603","England":"England","Sudbury, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Sudbury, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sudbury, Suffolk, England":"Sudbury, Suffolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1522–1591":"1522–1591","1530–1591":"1530–1591","1562–1603":"1562–1603","1560–1604":"1560–1604","1497–Male":"1497–Kuollut","1501–Female":"1501–Kuollut","from 1560 to 1575":"vuodesta 1560 vuoteen 1575","1571":"1571","1560":"1560","1591":"1591","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1522":"1522","1587":"1587","